We may suppose that it had not a similar effect on the property of a woman who merely made a coemption for the purpose of changing her guardian or acquiring testamentary capacity, though it may perhaps have been that the transfer took place but that the coemptionator was under a fiducia to retransfer it.

The genuine sale of a wife was probably forbidden at an early period under the severest religione sanctiens: this did not prevent the simulated sale (remancipatio) of a woman by her coemptionator, i. e. the simulating disposition when once established was free from the supervening rules of the simulated disposition.
